x4freetext: A 2.5 cm diameter*2.5 cm long stilbene crystal
and a 2.5 cm diameter*5.0 cm long NE213 liquid
scintillator. A further 5.0 cm diameter*2.5 cm long
NE213 monitor detector was arranged 20 cm from the
target perpendicular to the incident beam direction.
The targets were prepared by heating a 380 mu-m thick
tantalum strip in the presence of 13C enriched methyl
iodide, thereby cracking a durable carbon layer
enriched to 50.5% in 13C directly onto the strip.
Target thickness was determined by measuring
13C(a,n0)16O excitation functions with, respectively, a
thick and the unknown thin target over four sharp
resonances between Ea=3.5 and 5 MeV. By comparing
integrated yields in corresponding resonances, a thin
target value of 30.0+-1.7 mu-g/cm2 was derived,
entailing an energy loss of 25 keV at Ea=4.5 MeV and
15 keV at Ea=10.5 MeV.
The measured yields were corrected for the energy-
dependent detector efficiency, normalized to the
monitor counts, and converted to an absolute scale by
normalization to the 0 degr. yield curve.
Random experimental errors were in general quite small,
of the order of 1-2%, but the overall absolute error in
the cross section was determined by that assigned to
the excitation function and consequently ranged from
+- 10% at the lower incident energies to +- 30% at the
high-energy region.
